<h2>
    <a href="/blog/the-distribution-of-easter-dates/">The distribution of Easter dates</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    
    on 13 Sep 2019
</h6>





<a href="/blog/the-distribution-of-easter-dates/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/easter-dates/.thumbnails/easter-dates.png/easter-dates-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>Loosely speaking, in the Gregorian calendar, Easter falls on the first Sunday following the first full Moon on or after 21 March. There are various algorithms (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computus"><em>Computus</em></a>) which can be used to calculate its date, and the cycle of dates repeats every 5.7 million years.
The following code produces a bar chart of the distribution of Easter dates using one of these algorithms.</p>




